<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch Animal Development Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia announced Sunday
that a 300-million Birr (42 million U.S. Dollars) worth animal
resources development project will be launched in the coming
1999.
</P>
<P>
Haddera Gebru, head of animal and fishery resources
development department of the Ministry of Agriculture, said the
five-year project includes animal husbandry, fodder manufacturing
and improving veterinary services, the Ethiopia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia stands first in Africa and tenth in the world in its
livestock resources. Hides and skins export is the second
largest export item in the country second only to coffee.
</P>
<P>
Haddera said the project which helps promote the sustainable
development of the sector will be undertaken in all regions
including Addis Ababa and Dire Dawa, the two largest cities of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Regional agriculture bureaux and farmers will take part in the
project which also aims to strengthen hybridization centers and
expand modern animal rearing technology, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to Haddera, most of the fund needed for the project
is obtained in loan from the African Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Laboratories and sheds will also be maintained and
constructed, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
