<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Extremists Detained, Security Tightened for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police Sunday detained
a number of Jewish right-wing activists and beefed up security
measures to foil attempts by Jewish extremists to attack the top
leaders, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The activists were taken into custody for questioning in
connection with vandalism, attacks against Palestinians in the
West Bank town of Hebron or incitement during demonstrations
outside the residence of Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, the
radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army lifted in the day a curfew imposed 10 days ago
on the Israeli-controlled part of the town when a Jewish settler
was stabbed to death by someone who the Israelis alleged was a
Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, where more than 400 Jewish settlers live alongside
120,000 Palestinians, has witnessed sporadic clashes between the
two sides since Israel handed over most parts of the town to the
Palestinians last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, security has been tightened for Israeli President
Ezer Weizman, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and Mordechai
amid reports that Jewish extremists are planning to attack or even
assassinate them to head off a possible agreement with the
Palestinians on Israel's overdue withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel's General Security Service has reportedly advised
Netanyahu to limit his public appearance or wear bullet-proof vest
if he has to go out.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to take serious precautions to prevent any attack on
its leaders, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the extremists are also planning "massive murder
attacks against Arabs in the West Bank" and to attack Arab holy
sites to provoke Palestinian retaliation and create "a spiral of
violence that will sabotage the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohamed Hussein, director of the Al-Aqsa Mosque in Arab
East Jerusalem, was quoted by Israel Radio as saying Sunday that
the mosque has always been the target of Jewish extremists.
</P>
<P>
It is up to the Israeli government to prevent any attacks on
the mosque, which was destroyed by an Israeli arsonist 29 years
ago and rebuilt later, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
