<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Calls for Talks to Solve Election Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodom
Sihanouk on Sunday urged Cambodian political leaders to resolve
disputes through dialogues, in an effort to calm the political
unrest haunting the country in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
In a message delivered from Siemreap, Sihanouk called on those
ready to use violence to avoid such acts, saying that they are
against the Constitution and laws of the country and are
detrimental to the interest of the people.
</P>
<P>
Though the "serious events" happening in recent weeks could not
be termed as violence, the king said, they have drawn serious
criticism from the international community.
</P>
<P>
Sihanouk also voice worries that if friendly countries stopped
providing aid, Cambodians would plunge deeper into poverty and
desperation.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian politicians have to solve their differences through
talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, oppositions led by the FUNCINPEC party and the Sam
Rainsy Party have been staging massive protests against the
Cambodian People's Party (CPC), alleging that the CPC won the July
26 parliamentary elections through fraud.
</P>
<P>
The oppositions have refused to accept the preliminary election
results.
</P>
<P>
Protests started to escalate on Sunday. Chanting slogans
against Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and Vietnam, more than
10,000 demonstrators took to the street despite a ban by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Tensions heightened in Phnom Penh as protesters damaged the
Monument to Cambodian-Vietnamese Friendship, which stands close to
the parliamentary building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
