<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-30 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aqsa Mosque Reopens to Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Aqsa Mosque in East Jerusalem
was reopened on Sunday to visitors in response to a call by
Palestinian economic and tourist sectors in the city.
</P>
<P>
The famous mosque was closed to the public four days ago by
its authority in protest of the arrest of two Palestinian youths
by Israeli police and the presence of the Israeli border guards
inside the holy sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
The two Palestinian youths were arrested by Israeli police
Tuesday morning near the western entrance to the mosque and no
reasons for the arrests have been given.
</P>
<P>
After hearing the news, a large number of Palestinians
gathered inside the mosque to protest, forcing the authority of
the mosque to close it to visitors.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side said that because certain radical Jewish
groups are threatening to attack the mosque, the Israeli police
and border guards can not be removed right now from it.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, a Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
minister in charge of Jerusalem Affairs, told the Voice of
Palestine on Sunday that the Israeli claims are only excuses for
keeping its soliders in the compound of the mosque.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestinian side continues to contact the Israeli
side on this issue, urging Israel to withdraw the border guards
from the holy site.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Jerusalem sent a
letter on Sunday to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani, requesting them to pull out the border guards
from inside the mosque.
</P>
<P>
"The continuous presence of border guards could ... cause more
problems and conflicts," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Aqsa Mosque is one of the historical holy sites in East
Jerusalem managed by Palestinian religious figures. Tens of
thousands of visitors visit it everyday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
