<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM to Visit Northern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem is to visit northern Cyprus Monday to discuss the upcoming
delivery of Russian-made S-300 missiles, the Anatolia News Agency
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day visit to the north of the divided island,
Cem is expected to meet with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
on the sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
The visit follows a Turkish Foreign Ministry statement that
Ankara would not change its position on the missile deal between
Russia and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Turkey insisted the surface-to-air missiles will constitute a
serious threat to security of Turkey and Turkish Cypriots as well,
and vowed to prevent their deployment with all necessary means.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Russia will deliver the S-300 missiles to
Cyprus in November, in light of the 425 million U.S. dollar deal
signed by the two countries early last year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has since kept a 35,000-strong, heavily-armed force in
the northern part, where Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in
1983 a breakaway "Turkish Republic," recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
