<HEADLINE> Kabila Not to Attend NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Laurent Kabila, president of
the Democratic Republic of Congo, said Sunday he would not attend
the Non-Aligned Movement summit in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"No, I am not attending the summit. I am too busy organizing
resistance against foreign aggression in my country. We shall be
represented by our minister of state," Kabila told media in
Zimbabwe after talks with President Robert Mugabe, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
A Reuters report said Kabila's Justice Minister Mwende Kangolo
arrived in Durban Sunday to attend the NAM summit due to open on
the coming Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president of the vast central African country paid a brief
visit to Zimbabwe Sunday for talks with his dogged supporter,
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have offered Kabila military
backing and sent troops to fight the rebels who took up arms
against Kabila on August 2 in Congo.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses Rwanda and Uganda, his former allies which had
helped him oust late dictator Mobutu Sese Seko in May 1997, of
backing ethnic Tutsi-led rebels who started a revolt in the east.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have denied the charge but insisted that
they reserve the right to intervene if their national security is
threatened.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said Sunday the war in his country was over on the
western front and was moving to the rebels' eastern stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the government army had re-captured the
strategic hydro-electric Inga dam in the southwest of Congolese
capital Kinshasa. There were also reports that some of the rebel
soldiers had fled to the neighboring Congo Republic across the
Congo River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
