<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Confident in Overcoming Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin is confident in overcoming the current crisis
in the country, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview Chernomyrdin said Sunday evening that
"We know what first steps to take to improve the situation." I am
sure it is possible to overcome the crisis in the country," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin stressed that "We cannot waste time. The country
cannot live without a government."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the political accord worked on by heads of the
presidential administration, government and parliament in the
morning, Chernomyrdin said that "I am very glad that this document
was prepared by us, not working groups, or assistants or
consultants. We coordinated it in advance."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there remain differences in the agreement
but they "are not fundamental". It is a matter of "the main
political agreement to be approved by the president; his approval
is very important. In that case we will get down to business," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He agreed with calls of giving more powers to the government
and Duma, but said "today the Duma should be giving powers to
itself first of all - so that everyone would be doing one's job."
</P>
<P>
According to Chernomyrdin, the main working principles of
government in Russia should be clarity, concreteness and fastness.
If financial problems have to be resolved today, if decisions must
be made - no matter by whom - the government, the Duma or the
president, it should be done in one move, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On personnel of the government Chernomyrdin said the government
should be made of people "who know and understand how things should
be done, and not just what should be done."
</P>
<P>
An agreement on political compromises among the Russian
president, government and both chambers of parliament was reached
by the representatives of the tripartite commission at Sunday's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The document provides for a mutual non-aggression pact, that is
the president will not dissolve the State Duma before elections in
1999, the Duma will not raise the question on the government's
resignation, the cabinet will not put forward in the Duma the vote
of confidence in the government issue.
</P>
<P>
Now the political accord has been submitted to the Russian
president for confirmation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
