<HEADLINE> Turkey Pledges Financial Aid to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey will provide a total of
29.5 million U.S. dollars in loans and grants to help rebuild the
war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The financial aid is aimed at improving facilities of Bosnia's
national carrier Air Bosnia and repair buildings and bridges
damaged during the 1992-95 civil war, Ecevit told reporters upon
returning from a trip to the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit went to Bosnia to attend a ceremony marking Turkey's
Army Day held by Turkish troops stationed in the town of Zenica as
part of the multinational peacekeeping force, according to the
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Ecevit held separate meetings with Bosnian
President Alija Izetbegovic and Muslim-Croat Federation President
Ejup Ganic on bilateral ties and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with one of the co-prime
ministers, Haris Silajdzic, the Turkish deputy prime minister said
that Turkey is ready to offer an aid package to help heal the
wounds of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular country,
maintains close ties with Muslim-dominated Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
