<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese FM Denies Links with Bin Laden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail denied Sunday any links with Saudi-born
millionaire Osama bin Laden who is accused of planning the August
7 bomb attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Sudan has nothing to do with bin Laden," Ismail said at a
press conference here in the Kenyan capital, where he stopped
over on his way from Khartoum to Durban, South Africa for the
Non-Aligned Movement conference.
</P>
<P>
The United States accuses bin Laden of running a global
"terrorist" network from bases in Afghanistan and of using the el
Shifa pharmaceutical plant in the Sudanese capital as a terrorist
facility, a charge denied immediately by Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Washington attacked with cruise missiles the el Shifa plant
and another target in Afghanistan on August 20 in retaliation for
the embassy bombings, which killed 253 people, including 12
Americans, in Nairobi and another 10 in Dar es Salaam earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said there are no links between the raided plant and
bin Laden, who left Sudan in 1995 at the request of the Sudanese
government because of widespread allegations that he was involved
in other bomb attacks around the world.
</P>
<P>
"We told Osama bin Laden that our position is to have good
relations with the Arab nations and with our other neighbors, and
that is not compatible with you staying here," Ismail said.
</P>
<P>
"Osama bin Laden left Sudan in 1995 and he never came back...
We cut all links," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ismail also reiterated Sudan's call for a U.N. fact-finding
mission to investigate the activities of the el Shifa plant, a
call that has been backed by the Organization of African Unity
and the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has deferred a decision on Sudan's
request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
