<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Security Operation for NAM Summit in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The largest security operation
since the World War II swung into top gear in Durban Sunday as
the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit draws near.
</P>
<P>
Vernon Hunter, the provincial coordinator for NAM security,
said police in Durban were trying their best to make the city
safer with a "steel broom" being used to sweep drug peddlers,
prostitutes and vagrants off the streets.
</P>
<P>
A two-day senior officials meeting of the 12th NAM started
Saturday, to be followed by the NAM foreign ministers meeting
Monday and Tuesday and the summit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hunter said that 430 policemen and women had been put on
special crime-prevention detail to keep the city safe for the
delegates.
</P>
<P>
"With the influx of NAM delegates, they will be obvious
targets for criminals: carrying cameras around their necks and
speaking foreign languages," he said.
</P>
<P>
The police in Durban "are doing a sweep-up operation and are
trying to keep the city as crime-free as possible", he added.
</P>
<P>
Alex Wright, chief inspector of the Durban City Police, said:
"We don't want to get a negative impression of Durban as a
tourist destination, so we will try and look after our visitors
as best as we can."
</P>
<P>
The total security component for the NAM, including police,
bodyguards, intelligence agents and defense force is about 4,000
people, including 1,200 security personnel, according to Hunter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
