<HEADLINE> Nigerian Immigration Officers to Learn French </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 30 (Xinhua) -- All immigration officials of
Nigeria are now to study the French language to enhance their
ability to communicate with foreign nationals coming into this
West African country, a top immigration official said.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Sahabi Dange, Comptroller-General of the Nigeria
Immigration Service (NIS) said this at the weekend at a forum
organized by the News Agency of Nigeria in federal capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The official said the Federal Ministry of Education had
concluded arrangements for the take-off of the program as part of
the efforts to enhance the performance of the immigration
officials.
</P>
<P>
Further more, he said, ability to speak French will now be
considered in all recruitments into the NIS.
</P>
<P>
Dange appealed to Nigerians to show understanding to
immigrants from neighboring West African countries, most of the
which have French as their official language.
</P>
<P>
As citizens from co-member countries of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS), the immigrants have the rights
to reside and engage in business in Nigeria, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has drawn up plans to teach French as a foreign
language in all its schools, as a way to promote cooperations
with its French-speaking neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
