<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Leaders Encourage Russia to Carry on Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The Leaders of the Group of Seven
(G7)leading industrial nations have pledged to encourage Russia to
press ahead with its economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Sunday that British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who discussed the Russian financial
situation by telephone with other G7 leaders over the weekend,
said the G7 countries felt it was in all their interests to ensure
Russia sticks to its reform path.
</P>
<P>
"There is a clear feeling among the G7 leaders that it is in
all our interests to make sure Russia gets through this crisis and
it will best do so by sticking to the reform path," the spokesman
quoted Blair as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair, whose country is the current G7 president,
also discussed the Russian financial situation with the rotating
European Union (EU) president Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders stressed that the 15 nation-bloc and the G7
countries would work closely and coordinate their response to the
Russian financial difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
