<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East counties.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey will provide a total of 29.5 million U.S.
dollars in loans and grants to help rebuild the war-torn
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The financial aid is aimed at improving facilities of Bosnia's
national carrier Air Bosnia and repair buildings and bridges
damaged during the 1992-95 civil war, Ecevit told reporters upon
returning from a trip to the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algeria's tax revenues hit 8.5 billion Algeria
dinars (145 million dollars) during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
A release issued by the General Algerian Tax Department said
that last year's tax revenues stood at 15.1 billion dinars (258.1
million dollars), 2.1 billion dinars (359,000 dollars) more than
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- The General Corporation for Kuwaiti Ports made a
profit of 6 million Kuwait dinars (19.6 million dollars) during
the fiscal year of 1997 ending last June.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the corporation said the total
revenues in the year hit 34 million dinars (111 million dollars),
21 percent higher than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli currency, shekel, Friday further
depreciated by 2.7 percent against the dollar after losing 1
percent Thursday, standing at 3.875 shekels for one dollar.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation was caused due to the fear of investors and
speculators that the shekel would further devalue in the near
future. 
</P>
