<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NAM Meeting Working Out Document on Disarmament, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, August 30 (Xinhua)-- Senior officials attending the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) meeting are working hard to complete a
draft communique on issues including disarmament and debt relief,
for formal adoption by their leaders at NAM summit Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Observers said this document has already gone through several
drafts. The draft document provides broad themes of consensus on
issues like the need for the reform of the U.N., especially the
Security Council, to give developing countries a greater say.
</P>
<P>
It also includes international disarmament, particularly
programs to decommission nuclear arsenals, and Third World
development, including debt relief, trade access, technical
assistance and investment.
</P>
<P>
The need to ensure that globalization has a positive impact on
the poorest countries will also be a major issue at the summit.
</P>
<P>
A parade of heads of state or their representatives from
developing countries will sweep into Durban Tuesday to attend the
summit the following day.
</P>
<P>
A backdrop of terrorism and U.S. reactions, spiraling African
conflict and the prospect of a global economic meltdown will add
spice, even urgency, to their speeches.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, whose chairmanship of the Movement will start
when Colombia's tenure expires as the summit opens, might use its
mandate for the next three years to modernize the capacity,
culture and content of the Movement.
</P>
<P>
It is clear, especially from South Africa's proposed
amendments, that reformers within the NAM are pushing to move it
out of the realm of demands and rhetoric. Instead, there is a
new emphasis on engagement with, rather than condemnation of, the
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in NAM's history, the U.S., Britain, and
France will attend the global organization's summit, as will
representatives of the European Union, and the G-8 grouping of
the world's most highly developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The invitation extended to these countries to attend as guests
appears largely to have been the initiative of the host country,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Minty, South Africa's Deputy Director-General of Foreign
Affairs, who is in charge of the summit's policy deliberations,
said Friday that the presence of representatives of the most
powerful western nations will make it possible for real
interaction to take place between the developed and developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
What is also emphasized is an acknowledgement of the
responsibility of NAM nations to contribute to this process by
getting their own financial and political houses in order.
</P>
<P>
Through NAM, South Africa hopes to put development at the
center of a new framework of global diplomacy to replace the
vacuum left by the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's attempts to reform the 113-nation NAM is a goal
as ambitious as the African Renaissance, the observers noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans, Democrats Voice Separate Views on Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The third-ranking Republican
of the House of Representatives wants Congress to stay in session
until it completes action on Independent Counsel's report expected
soon about President Bill Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay said the House should take up the
Lewinsky matter as soon as Starr submits a report and should not
go home for the year until it has reached a conclusion on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
"If the president is going to put us through this trauma, then
we need to get it over with as soon as possible," DeLay said on
"Fox News Sunday." "We need to stay in session for as long as it
takes to get this behind us."
</P>
<P>
DeLay, a leading conservative, repeated his position that
Clinton should resign.
</P>
<P>
But Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
said on NBC's "Meet the Press," that Clinton, who leaves Monday
for a trip to Russia, remains an effective world leader, "an
enormously strong president internationally and in his own
country."
</P>
<P>
The House returns from summer vacation after Labor Day and
plans to be in session for only a month before going home for the
midterm elections. Other Republican leaders, including House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, have shown little enthusiasm for initiating
contentious impeachment hearings before the elections.
</P>
<P>
Starr has not indicated when he will submit his report or
whether it will go beyond the president's admitted improper
relationship with the former White House intern and associated
allegations of obstruction of justice, perjury or suborning
perjury.
</P>
<P>
Once the report goes to Congress, the House Judiciary Committee
must decide whether it contains sufficient evidence to bring
impeachment proceedings before the full House. Once there, the
House would have to vote on whether to impeach, turning the matter
over to the Senate for final judgment on the president's expulsion
from office.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday's news shows, Democrats promised not to allow
Judiciary hearings to become a simple indictment of the president.
On Fox, Representative John Dingell said Starr and his staff
should be questioned about their conduct of the investigation.
Representative Marty Meehan said on ABC's "This Week with Sam
Donaldson and Cokie Roberts" that a minority viewpoint should go
forward with the report" so that the president has an opportunity
to present the other side."
</P>
<P>
Representative Lois Slaughter, a Democrat, said on the same
program that if Starr comes up with nothing beyond the Lewinsky
affair, "It will be forgotten and it will be dropped like a bad
memory."
</P>
<P>
Representative Jim McGovern, a Democrat, said he and Senator
John Kerry, a Democrat, urged the president to come forth with
more about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"The president admitted to us that the timing of his speech was
probably not the best and that he wished he had more time to
reflect and get his emotions together before he addressed the
American people," McGovern said on NBC.
</P>
<P>
DeLay and Dingell agreed that Starr's report and parts of the
grand jury testimony on the case should be made public. "I would
like to see the executive summary of the report minus any
pornography revealed to the American people immediately," DeLay
said.
</P>
<P>
Dingell said that while the grand jury testimony should be
reviewed, for the Starr report "synopsis is not sufficient. The
whole of his report must be made public." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
