<HEADLINE> Chissano Calls for Dialog in Solving Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Sunday called for dialog and negotiations to solve
conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The warring sides should support the recent resolution adopted
by the Southern African Development Community (SADC) at a
mini-summit in Pretoria, South Africa, he said at a dinner in
honor of visiting Algerian President Liamine Zeroual.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to Rwanda and Burundi, the two countries in the
Great Lakes region which are having civil strifes, to resort to
dialog and tolerance as the only means to conflict settlement,"
Chissano added.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president also expressed worries over the
worsening political and military situation in Angola, where the
opposition National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) has been delaying implementation of the 1994 Lusaka
peace accord and therefore plunging the Angolan peace process
into a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Only candid and rational talks can put an end to the war and
the sufferings of the Angolan people, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chissano, it takes concerted and unremitting
efforts by countries, regions and international organizations
concerned to solve conflicts in Africa and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
He hopes that the next Organization of African Unity (OAU)
summit in Algiers could be held with less or even without
conflicts and terrorism and discuss issues concerning Africa's
economic, social and cultural development.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also extends the wish to enhance bilateral
cooperations with Algeria especially in fisheries, energy,
industry, transport, education and trade.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian president arrived here Sunday afternoon on his
way to go to Durban, South Africa to attend the Non-Aligned
Movement summit Wednesday. The two heads of state will hold
formal talks here Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
