<HEADLINE> Blair, Clinton Exchange Views on Russian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and U.S. President Bill Clinton Sunday discussed the Russian
financial crisis by telephone, urging Russia to carry on its
reform program.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman was quoted by Reuters as saying
Sunday evening: "There was clear agreement (between Blair and
Clinton) that we're ready to help Russia, but only if Russia is
ready to pursue further economic reform."
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, Blair, whose country is the current
Group of Seven (G7) president, had a series of telephone
discussions with other G7 leaders.
</P>
<P>
"There is a clear agreement among the G7 leaders that it is in
all our interests to make sure Russia gets through this crisis and
it is best do so by sticking to the reform path," another Downing
Street spokesman said early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair also discussed the Russian financial situation
with the rotating European Union (EU) president Austrian
Chancellor Viktor Klima.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders pledged that the EU and the G7 countries would
coordinate their response to the Russian financial difficulties.
</P>
