<HEADLINE> Sion Bids to Host 2006 Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Sion of Switzerland made its
official bid to host the 2006 Winter Olympic Games in Lausanne on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sports minister Adolf Ogi, who replaced FIFA president Sepp
Blatter as head of the Swiss bid on Saturday, handed over a 600
page document to representatives of the International Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for bids is midnight on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, representatives of three other bids also
presented their candidacies, namely Turin, Helsinki in
combination with Lillehammer in Norway, and the Polish city of
Zakopane.
</P>
<P>
Klagenfurt of Austria was the first to present its candidacy
on Friday and Slovakian town of Poprad Tatry is expected to hand
in its documents on Tuesday, bringing the total number of
candidates to six.
</P>
<P>
Sion, which failed in bids to host the 1976 and 2002 Winter
Games, is widely seen as the favourite for the 2006 Games.
</P>
<P>
The decision will be taken by the IOC in June next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
