<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Rejects Chernomyrdin as Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma on Monday
overwhelmingly voted against President Boris Yeltsin's candidate
for prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin after heated debates in the
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Only 94 deputies voted for Chernomyrdin, way below the
required 226 votes from 450 lawmakers. Of the 345 deputies who
cast votes 251 voted against, with no abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The rejection would certainly push Russia into further
political stand-off between the Duma and Yeltsin, who is likely
to Chernomyrdin's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
The vote, originally scheduled for 18:00 local time (14:00
GMT), was taken one hour later to allow deputies to vent, for the
most part, their anger at the government and President Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party, the largest
opposition faction with 133 of the 450 seats, said Chernomyrdin
"does not possess a single quality necessary for leading the
government."
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov blasted the government's performance in the past seven
years, both under Chernomyrdin from 1992 until March this year,
and under Sergei Kiriyenko, who was dismissed abruptly August 23.
</P>
<P>
"What has been going on in the country for seven years under
the disguise of economic reforms is now lying in ruin," Zyuganov
said. "The main cause is the (cabinet's) policy, the absence of
basic governance and a total lack of responsibility among the
country's rulers."
</P>
<P>
Yabloko leader Grigory Yavlinsky accused Chernomyrdin of
creating "an extremely inefficient economic system, a
semi-criminal one" during his previous term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Zhirinovsky, of the nationalist Liberal Democratic
Party, simply nominated himself as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that my candidature may be confirmed at the
next session if President Yeltsin and I take the necessary
measures and make the right conclusions from today's discussions,"
Zhirinovsky said.
</P>
<P>
The Agrarians, another opposition faction, said they did not
trust Chernomyrdin and they "have no confidence whatsoever" that
even if confirmed he would be able to remedy the situation in
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
