<HEADLINE> Microsoft Launches Windows 98 Chinese Version </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The fact that Windows 98 has
attracted great attention in the world's most populous country is
far from surprising.
</P>
<P>
The long anticipated Chinese version of Microsoft's latest
personal computer operating system was ushered today during a
dazzling ceremony which included a red Ferrari, music reminding
one of James Bond movies, fireworks, disco music and a light
show.
</P>
<P>
The English version was launched in the United States a little
over two months ago on June 25. Today's introduction means "we
have significantly narrowed the gap between the time Microsoft's
products are available in the United States and other parts of the
world," said Michael Rawding, regional director of Microsoft
Greater China.
</P>
<P>
Windows 95 was introduced in China in 1996, almost eight months
after it appeared in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Windows 98 "will have a stronger influence" than it's
predecessor in terms of preinstallation by personal computer
manufacturers, according to Juliet Wu, general manager of
Microsoft (China) Co. Limited.
</P>
<P>
Wu expressed appreciation for the contributions of major local
PC producers such as Legend, Founder, Tongtru, and multinational
hardware manufacturers such as AMD and Compaq in the development
and preinstallation of the new product.
</P>
<P>
Legend and Microsoft dedicated over six months to ensure the
"smooth integration" of the hardware and latest software,
according to Yang Yuanqing, senior vice president of the Legend
Group.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts point out that preinstalling the most
advanced operating system is a common practice amongst the world's
major PC manufacturers, and the concurrent availability of
preinstalled computers in China with the release of the Windows 98
Chinese version is ample evidence of the maturing market
activities of the local industry.
</P>
<P>
They also point out that concurrent availability is in best
interests of genuine software and is conducive to the growth of
China's software industry.
</P>
<P>
Windows 98 offers more and better network functions than
Windows 95, as well as better integration of work and recreational
functions.
</P>
<P>
Windows 98 may not, however, represent the benchmark that
Windows 95 represented for some people, said Martin Wu, China
marketing manager for Intel. Nonetheless, its graphic and Internet
applications provide amply proof it is a "good product," said Wu.
</P>
</TEXT>
