<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows to Withdraw All Combat Troops from East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Armed Forces will
withdraw all its combat troops from East Timor in due time, a
military commander said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have long been planning to withdraw our troops (from East
Timor) and this is not due to foreign pressure," the Antara News
Agency quoted Major General Adam Damiri as saying.
</P>
<P>
Damiri is the chief of the Udayana regional military command
which oversees Bali, East and West Nusa Tenggara and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia recently pulled out 1,500 troops from East Timor, but
four battalions consisting of about 4,000 troops remain there.
</P>
<P>
Once it withdraws all the combat troops, Damiri said, the
military will only retain health and spiritual detachments and a
territorial task force.
</P>
<P>
"Their task however is only to assist East Timoreses in
non-combatant fields," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian troops entered East Timor in 1975 after the
departure of the Portuguese colonists and annexed the territory
the following year.
</P>
<P>
Though Indonesia declared East Timor its 27th province in 1976,
the United Nations has been demanding Jakarta withdraw troops from
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
During the August 4-5 tripartite dialogue in New York, Portugal
agreed to study Indonesia's proposal to grant East Timor special
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, East Timor would enjoy autonomy, which
allows it full governance except in the fields of foreign affairs,
external defense and some monetary policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
