<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:  Uganda Deeply Concerned Over Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- As the situation in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) experiences twists and turns,
the Ugandan authorities have shown deep concern over the armed
conflict between the government troops and the Tutsi-led rebels.
</P>
<P>
The raging war in DRC is feared to spill over into a regional
conflict. Uganda has urged for a political solution to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the eruption of the armed conflict on August 2,
Uganda's attention has been drawn to it because DRC has accused
Uganda of instigating the rebellion and being militarily involved
in the war, a charge Kampala quickly denied.
</P>
<P>
Last week, both Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Eriya Kategaya and Major General
Salim Saleh revealed on separate occasions that Uganda has a
sizable military presence in eastern DRC. But it is there to
"safeguard Uganda's national security", they said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has reportedly two battalions there working with
President Laurent Kabila's soldiers to flush out rebels of Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF) under an April security pact between the
two governments.
</P>
<P>
ADF rebels, operative since January 1996, have conducted
abductions and looted properties of the impoverished people in
Uganda's western districts of Kases, Kabarole and Bundibugyo,
government sources said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda hoped both warring parties can accept the call for
peace made by the recent summit meeting of the Southern African
Development Community and solve the issue at negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is experiencing its biggest ever economic boom and it
does not want to drag its economy into shambles again by being
sucked into the war.
</P>
<P>
The peace and stability in the Great Lakes Region is crucial
to Uganda's economy, one of the few success stories on the
continent. Its privatization and liberalization added power to
its growing economy.
</P>
<P>
DRC is Uganda's key trading partner in the region. There is no
reason for Uganda to attack such a neighbor and trade partner
just in order to lose it, President's Press Secretary Hope
Kivengere told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia are reported to have
sent military support to DRC and some of the rebels' strongholds
began to fall into Kabila's hands. Foreign involvement is feared
to regionalize the war and make things more complicated,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
They fear that the ethnic war, no end in sight, will surely
affect regional economic cooperation and cast a dark shadow over
the region.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Kabila's army has begun to advance to the eastern
city of Goma after claiming victory in Kinshasa. This will
definitely invite more and closer attention from the
international community including Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
