<HEADLINE> EU Official Calls for Emergency Meeting on Russian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- A senior European Commission
official has called for an emergency meeting of the European Union
to study the exacerbating Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Commission spokesman Patrick Child told the press on Monday
that Yves-Thibault de Silguy, European commissioner responsible
for economic, financial and monetary policy of the European Union,
consulted with Austria, which is serving the rotating presidency
of the union, on a meeting of European finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner suggested to hold the meeting prior to
Thursday's meeting of the European Commission, the executive body
of the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the commissioner had asked for an informal
meeting among finance ministers to study the case.
</P>
<P>
The commission has kept saying that the Russian financial
crisis is not affecting the economy of the European Union very
much and the crisis still remains a problem of the Russians.
</P>
<P>
Officials said on several occasions that the commission was not
considering to offer more funds to bail Russia out of the current
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The commission has been giving Russia technical assistance
through its TACIS program that also covers central and eastern
European countries.
</P>
<P>
The total yearly available funds for the TACIS program is 500
million ECU (550 million U.S. dollars) with a third of the sum
usually going to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia has received 400 million ECU (440 million dollars) in
1998 alone, commission officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
