<HEADLINE> Higher Vigil Called For As Floods Begin Retreating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The State Flood Control and
Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH) today called for greater
vigilance in monitoring the flood situation along the Yangtze River
and the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
In this year's fourth plenary meeting of the SFCDRH presided
over by Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao, director of the SFCDRH,
participants warned against a slack in vigilance as flood waters
recede along the major rivers.
</P>
<P>
The participants pointed out that the risk of breaches and
possibility of collapses along levees is even higher in sections
of levees waterlogged for an extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
They urged continued 24-hour monitoring of levees along the
Yangtze, Songhua rivers and around Dongting and Poyang lakes, as
well as continued efforts to reinforce dangerous sections in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Preparations should be made to ensure the availability of
adequate stockpiles of reinforcement materials, as well as plans
for plugging breaches and rescue efforts if needed.
</P>
<P>
The SFCDRH called on hydrologists and experts to increase
technical guidance and urged leading officials to strengthen
supervision in order to ensure the ultimate success of the flood
control effort.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the eighth flood crest that passed
through Shashi in Hubei Province this morning has pushed the
waters in Jinjiang in the middle reaches of the Yangtze River to
surge again, threatening the already worn-out dykes in the
section.
</P>
<P>
Currently about 2.32 million soldiers and civilians are
reinforcing dangerous levees and closely monitoring flood status
along the river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
