<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Anti-Smuggling (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The monthly magazine Qiushi,
China's leading official publication, in its 17th issue for the
year to be published on September 1 carries the full text of
Premier Zhu Rongji's July speech at the National Anti-smuggling
Work Conference calling for prompt and relentless crackdown on
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Zhu urged departments and governments at all levels to fully
realize the urgency and significance of the anti-smuggling
campaign. He said both the Party and central government are
determined to wipe out rampant smuggling and noted the success
will have a direct bearing on the realization of this year's
growth target, as well as the smooth development of China's
reform, opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
He said the campaign is also essential for building a clean
Party and government.
</P>
<P>
Zhu outlined the grave situation and pointed out that rampant
smuggling has reached a zenith in terms of the scope and quantity
of goods, as well as the unscrupulous means employed by smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The list of over a hundred targeted goods includes oil
products, edible oil, motor vehicles, motorcycles, textile and
chemical raw materials, pirated CDs and cigarettes. The estimated
value of goods smuggled into China each year exceeds 100 billion
yuan (12 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Rampant smuggling has also led to massive losses in terms of
tax revenues. Related activities have also hindered the growth of
national industries and aggravated difficulties facing state-owned
enterprises. Smuggling has also corrupted Party and government
officials, poisoned social morals and lead to a surge in criminal
activities.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the anti-smuggling campaign is not only a major
economic struggle, but also a harsh political struggle," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
The premier listed the root causes of rampant smuggling and
pointed out certain individuals in the Party and government
organizations, judicial departments and even military units have
been heavily involved in smuggling. Certain officials interested
only in group or personal gains have turned a blind eye to
illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
At least part of the blame can also be placed on weak law
enforcement. Certain law enforcement and judicial departments have
simply fined smugglers, rather than prosecuting the perpetrators
to the fullest extent by the law in court. Their actions have
simply encouraged the spread of smuggling, said Zhu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
