<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Anti-smuggling (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The premier outlined the focal points of the massive
anti-smuggling campaign set for the second half of the year. He
pointed out that law enforcement efforts will focus on areas rife
with smuggling, including Guangdong Province and coastal areas in
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, especially in waters off
Zhuhai in the former and China-Vietnam border areas in the latter.
</P>
<P>
Zhu urged public security bureaus and judicial departments to
pay special attention to two particular types of smugglers:
enterprises, mostly Sino-foreign joint ventures, which engage in
smuggling under the cover of legal entities in the processing
trade, and companies operated by certain Party and government
organizations, the armed forces and even public security
departments.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign should focus on companies with a history of
related activities. Leading officials with work units that own
related companies should be assigned full responsibility for their
involvement in smuggling," said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He called for relentless punishment for major cases and leaders
of major smuggling rings, as well as for the "execution of
notorious smugglers in accordance with the law." He added that no
one should shield criminals or interfere with law enforcement
investigations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu disclosed the following three important measures the
central government will take to reform the current anti-smuggling
effort and standardize related practices -- form a national
anti-smuggling police force; authorize Customs departments to
handle all smuggling cases with the support of public security
departments and industrial and commercial administrative
departments; and ensure all fines, goods and property confiscated
concerning smuggling cases are turned over to the state treasury,
and the central financial department will give back part of the
proceeds to the localities to boost the anti-smuggling campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
