<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for Closer Economic Ties with Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri called Monday for closer cooperation with Romania in trade
and economy.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with visiting Romanian Prime Minister Radu
Vasile, Hariri told a news conference that they discussed
bilateral ties, especially economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that Romania will increase imports from
Lebanon and remove all obstacles preventing Lebanese goods from
entering Romanian market.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Lebanon imports an annually 100
million U.S. dollars worth of Romanian goods while its exports
stand at 10 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that during the meeting, he explained to his
Romanian counterpart Lebanon's stance on the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Vasile said that Romania understands and supports Lebanon's
stance and called for the revival of the peace talks among the
concerned parties in a bid to realize a comprehensive and lasting
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected an Israeli offer made last April to
withdraw troops from south Lebanon on condition that Lebanon
guarantee the security of its northern areas. Lebanon insists the
Israeli withdrawal be unconditional under the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer self-declared security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985, allegedly to protect its northern
areas from attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Vasile arrived here earlier in the day for a two-day visit,
during which he also will hold talks with Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi. 
</P>
