<HEADLINE> Eighth Flood Crest Passes Yichang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The eighth Yangtze River flood
crest of the year passed Yichang, Hubei Province, today raising
water levels between Shishou and Jianli in middle and lower
reaches of the river, with levels in sections below Luoshan
continuing to recede slowly.
</P>
<P>
The 43rd flood circular issued today by the State Flood Control
and Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH) indicated that Hubei's
Gezhouba Hydropower Project reduced the flow rate by 2,700
cu.m./second and greatly relieved the intense pressure on
waterlogged levees in the Jinjiang Section. The report indicated
that related levees have been virtually saturated for over two
months.
</P>
<P>
The flood crest passed Yichang at 06:00 this morning, with the
flow rate hitting 57,400 cu.m./second. The flood crest passed
Shashi at noon raising water levels to 44.41 meters, or 0.81
meters lower than the high for the year. The noon flow rate in the
section stood at 45,200 cu.m./second.
</P>
<P>
The flow rate at Yichang slowed to 56,600 cu.m./second by 14:00
today. The circular listed slight drops in water levels for three
sections, with levels of 44.39 meters in Shashi, 28.98 meters in
Hankou and 22.25 meters in Jiujiang. Water levels in both Dongting
Lake and Poyang Lake remained essentially the same as yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Flood waters along the main courses in Nenjiang and Songhua
rivers receded somewhat today. The water level in Qiqihar was
below danger level at 146.45 meters by 14:00 this afternoon. The
water level in Harbin was 119.93 meters, or 0.96 meters below the
record, with the 80.13 meter level at Jiamusi missing the record
by 0.21 meters.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers and civilians continue to monitor levees on 24-hour
basis, with special attention on danger areas and replenishing
stockpiles of materials for rescue operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
