<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Euro Zone Remains Stable in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The annual inflation rate for
the 11-country euro zone remained stable at 1.4 percent in July,
Eurostat reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau for the European
communities said that the inflation for the 15-nation European
Union dropped to 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, however, registered the highest inflation in either
the euro zone or the union at 2.8 percent while France and Austria
both had the lowest rate at 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
EU-wide, the inflation decreased from 1.6 percent a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The largest relative increase of inflation was recorded in
Portugal, from 1.4 percent to 2.8 percent in the past 12 months,
while the largest decrease was found in Germany from 1.5 percent
to 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for the European Economic Area (the 15 EU
member states plus Norway and Iceland) also witnessed a decrease,
from 1.7 percent to 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat designed a special method to measure the inflation for
the euro zone. The measurement, known as MUICP, is calculated as a
weighted average of the Eurostat harmonized indices of consumer
prices of the 11 participating countries in the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Belgium, Germany, France, Spain, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg,
the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland are participating
in the single currency mechanism that starts on January 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
EU member states Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece did not
join in.
</P>
<P>
The European Central Bank and other European community
institutions will use the MUICP measurement as a main indicator
for monitoring inflation in the context of their monetary policy
management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
