<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice President Visits Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan left here for Khartoum on a two-day visit to Sudan for
consultations with Sudan on combating anti-Iraq and anti-Sudan
actions of the U.S. and Israel, Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Ramadan as saying that his visit to
Sudan came within the context of consultation and dialog between
the two countries on confronting the schemes and atrocities
carried out by the Americans and the Zionists.
</P>
<P>
He will hold talks with Sudanese President Omar Hassan Ahmed
al-Bashir, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., accusing Sudan of sponsoring international terrorism,
fired cruise missiles on August 20 at a pharmaceutical factory in
Khartoum in what it claimed retaliation for bombings on August 7
of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people were killed and more than 5,000 others
wounded in the twin bombings of the U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Sudan, Ramadan will fly to South Africa to take
part in the 12th summit of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM).
</P>
<P>
Ramadan said that in South Africa, his delegation would hold
extensive talks with a number of brotherly and friendly
delegations with the aim of developing relations between Iraq and
these states in all fields.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that the Iraqi delegation would seriously
contribute to the NAM summit agenda, mainly the paragraphs
relating to freedom and independence of peoples.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan pointed out that the Iraqi delegation would brief the
NAM states on the latest developments in relations between Iraq
and the Security Council and the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
for disarming Iraq and on Iraq's legitimate demands of the lifting
of the international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Iraq had implemented all commitments under
U.N. resolutions and the Security Council should lift the
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqi people have been suffering from the eight-year
embargo due to America's hegemony over the Security Council and
its insistence to prolong it," said Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, Iraq decided to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM
and the International Atomic Energy Agency, complaining that
UNSCOM is dominated by the United States and used by it as a tool
to prolong sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the sanctions imposed on Iraq following its 1990
invasion of Kuwait can not be lifted unless UNSCOM certifies that
it is free of chemical and biological weapons and long-range
missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
