<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Countries Meet on Customs Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The SAARC Group on Customs
Cooperation held deliberations recently on the formulation of an
action plan to ensure uniformity, harmony and simplification of
customs rules and procedures among the member states for regional
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Several activities to this end were identified at the group's
third meeting held in Jaipur, India on August 24-26, the
Kathmandu-based SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation) Secretariat said in a press release Monday.
</P>
<P>
The activities include preparation of a commodity description
code, expanding the 6-digit H.S. Code to accommodate description
of goods in vogue within the SAARC region, and adoption of baggage
laws, procedure and allowances, and law, procedure and exemption
limits on gifts and postal goods, the secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the group also identified matters related to
temporary import of vehicles and other goods and subsequent
re-export of them in the same state.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural address, Sukumar Shankar, member of the
Central Board of Excise and Customs of India, stressed the growing
importance of regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
He noted that of the over 75 free trade zones or customs unions
listed by the World Trade Organization, more than half were
established in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that if the free trade arrangement is to be
operationalized in the SAARC region by the targeted date, the
customs laws and procedures must be harmonized.
</P>
<P>
At their ninth summit in May, 1997, leaders of the SAARC member
states -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan
and Sri Lanka -- decided to establish a South Asian Free Trade
Area (SAFTA) preferably by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
At their 10th summit held in Colombo, Sri Lanka in late July
this year, the leaders skirted the time-frame for SAFTA, but
decided on drafting a comprehensive treaty regime by 2001 for
creating a free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Group on Customs Cooperation also decided at its
meeting that its chairmanship would be for a period of two years
and rotated alphabetically among the member states, and that Sri
Lanka would take over the chairmanship from Pakistan at the end of
this year, the SAARC Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the group will be organized by the SAARC
Secretariat in April/May 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
