<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Accepts Amarjargal's Nomination as PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagabandy on Monday accepted the nomination of Renchinnyamin
Amarjargal as the country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman said that Mongolia's National
Democratic Party and the Social Democratic Party nominated the
36-year-old Amarjargal, a Great Hural member and acting minister
of external relations, in a letter to the president on August 28.
</P>
<P>
The president has agreed to the nomination and submitted it to
the Great Hural for approval, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Amarjargal, born in 1961, graduated from a Moscow university
and was the president of the Mongolian Economy Institute. He was
elected to the Great Hural in July 1996 and appointed as the
minister of external relations in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Amarjargal is one of the founders of the National Progress
Party and the National Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The president dismissed the government led by Tsakhya Elbegdorj
on July 24, blaming it for worsening the country's banking crisis
by deciding to merge the state-owned Renovation Bank with the
private Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
The president had rejected seven times the nomination of
Davaadorj Ganbold, the chairman of the Standing Committee of
Economic Policy of the Great Hural, as premier.

