<HEADLINE> Arafat, Hassan Discuss U.S. Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan and
visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat held talks here Monday
to discuss Israel's possible acceptance of a U.S. peace proposal
on its next troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The talks also covered other aspects of the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, the official
Jordan Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Information Nasir Judeh said earlier
Monday that Arafat`s visit came in the context of continued
consultations between the Jordanian and Palestinian leaderships
in light of the recent developments which required coordination
among all the concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
Other details of the meeting were not disclosed yet.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and his delegation arrived here Monday afternoon for a
brief working visit, en route to South Africa to attend the summit
of The Non-aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was also scheduled to meet new Jordanian Prime Minister
Fayez Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process has been deadlocked since
early 1997 due to Israeli settlement expansion and delay in
carrying out the long overdue troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
To break the deadlock, the U.S. put forward a peace proposal in
January calling for a 13.1 percent withdrawal from the West
Bank. While Arafat has already accepted the proposal, Israel has
refrained publicly endorsing it citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
But latest developments signaled that Israel is close to
accepting the U.S. proposal conditionally. On Monday, Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told his cabinet that he was
willing to accept the U.S. proposal on condition that the
Palestinians meet certain requirements.
</P>
<P>
Israel is expected to demand the Palestinian side revise the
clauses in the Palestinian Covenant calling for Israeli
destruction and crack down tougher on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, the second Arab country to seal peace with Israel after
Egypt, has been playing a role in mediating the peace process,
taking advantage of its close ties with both parties.
</P>
<P>
While Jordan is a strong supporter of the Palestinian cause, it
is also Israel's best friend in the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
