<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Enjoy Better Social Status (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ACWF leader pointed out that education and health care
levels for women have also improved. China had 1.18 million female
college students and more than 50,000 female graduate students at
the end of 1997, with the figures accounting for 36 percent and 30
percent of the respective totals.
</P>
<P>
The enrollment rate of school-age girls stands at 98.6 percent
and a national health care network for women and children has been
established in both urban and rural areas. Some 24.8 million
people in 1,240 cities and counties across the nation have had
access to the social insurance of repreduction.
</P>
<P>
She said that the protection of women's rights in terms of
marriage and family have been improved. She noted that legal
marriages based on love, and equal and harmonious family relations
have emerged as the major trend in China.
</P>
<P>
Committees of women's federations at all levels have developed
rapidly, with the number of committees standing at 66,000. In
addition, there are currently 100,000 women's organizations in
various types of ventures, including township and private
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Gu said that a number of problems and difficulties must be
solved in order to further improve the social status of women.
</P>
<P>
The problems include the rising number of laid-off women,
difficulties in finding new jobs, the considerable number of
poverty-stricken women in rural areas and the comparatively low
participation rate of women in political affairs.
</P>
<P>
Gu stressed that a wide gap remains in education levels for
urban and rural women, and violation of that rights of women has
not as yet been eliminated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
