<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Sudanese President's Special Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Qian Qichen met
today with Awed Ahmed Al-Jaz, special envoy of Sudanese President
Omar Hassan Ahmed Al-Bashir, and said China is highly concerned
and deeply disturbed that the capital of Sudan has suffered from a
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Al-Jaz conveyed a letter from Sudanese
President Al-Bashir to Chinese President Jiang Zemin, expounding
Sudan's view of the missile attack.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jaz, who is also Sudanese Minister of Energy and Mines, said
Sudan pursues an independent foreign policy of peace, noting that
Sudan does not invade other countries nor interfere in their
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Sudan opposes any form of terrorism and all
actions encroaching upon its sovereignty, said Al-Jaz. He added
that Sudan praises China's just and responsible position on
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his thanks to President Al-Bashir for writing a
letter to President Jiang, saying that he will deliver the letter
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that China opposes terrorism in any form, and
believes that the international community should discover and
eliminate the source of terrorism and strengthen international
cooperation to fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
China also believes that all problems and disputes between
countries should be solved through consultations and in accordance
with the U.N. Charter and norms governing international relations,
said Qian, adding that China opposes the use of forces.
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed that China, as a permanent member of the
U.N. Security Council, joins the international community to
safeguard world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed Al-Jaz on China's efforts to fight against
the ongoing severe flooding, and expressed his thanks to the
Sudanese leader, government and people for their concern and
sympathy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
