<HEADLINE> Large State Businesses Become Earnings Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Newly listed large state
businesses have become the earnings stars on the Chinese stock
market for the first six months of this year, reporting
substantially better yields than the average market level.
</P>
<P>
For the 14 such state-owned companies that each have listed a
minimum of 100 million shares this year, they reported an average
per share yield of 0.17 yuan, about 1.62 times the average for the
810 companies that have reported earnings so far.
</P>
<P>
Their average rate of return was 6.7 percent for the first six
months, 1.6 times the average level for the whole market.
</P>
<P>
The market reported sliding company efficiency during the
January-June period this year, with an average per share yield of
0.105 yuan and a rate of return of 4.24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Handan Steel, with a net profit growth of 120 percent over the
same period last year, led the group of large state firms,
reporting a per share yield of 0.318 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts said that at least two factors laid solid
foundations for the improvement of these companies: they are all
involved in backbone industries, and they have undergone
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"The government policies aimed at stimulating domestic demand
and the two rounds of rate cuts also helped a lot," according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
In a large scenario, the market also saw fewer blue chip stocks
this year and many more loss-making companies, which have risen to
71 from the 38 in January-June 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
