<HEADLINE> Non-Aligned Members Urged to Close Gap Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN (South Africa), August 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa,
chairman state of the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), Monday
called on member countries to spare no efforts to narrow the gap
between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the NAM foreign ministers meeting, South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said NAM countries should strive to
attain sustainable rates of economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
"All of us have to work to eliminate poverty in our countries,
to improve the quality of life of the millions of our people, to
close the gap between the rich and the poor both internationally
and universally."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki pointed out that the developed countries could not
maintain and expand their prosperity while billions of others are
victims to dire misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
He said sustained prosperity in the West might help bring
stability and renewed growth to Asia and elsewhere, but the
spreading crisis was also likely to export instability to the
West.
</P>
<P>
The deputy president appealed that the world economy should be
managed in a way that ensures the transfer of resources from those
who have them to those that have not.
</P>
<P>
"We must make the fairly obvious point that the untapped markets
in the world economy are those of the developing world, represented
by us who are members of the Non-Aligned Movement," he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the eradication of poverty and backwardness, Mbeki
stressed that NAM countries should rely on themselves rather than the
developed.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 44 NAM member states and seven observer countries
participated in the meeting, which is to focus on various issues of
international concern, including sustainable development of regional
and world economy and peace settlement of regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, topics of disarmament, non-proliferation of nuclear
weapons and the United Nations' reform, will also be on top of
agenda.  
</P>
