<HEADLINE> China to Launch Agriculture Law Enforcement Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) will inspect the implementation
of the Agriculture Law in September in Jiangsu, Guangdong and
Yunnan provinces, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, the
NPC Standing Committee announced today.
</P>
<P>
This will be the NPC Standing Committee's fifth inspection
since the Agriculture Law was promulgated in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee held a plenary meeting of the four
inspection teams today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, said China's
agriculture and rural economy are sound overall. However, some
obstacles that have long hindered agricultural development,
especially this year's enormous floods, have put agricultural
production into severe difficulty, he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that agricultural production is directly related
to fulfilling the 8 percent national economic growth rate goal,
because agriculture is the basis of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, this year's Agriculture Law enforcement inspection
is specially important, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the fundamental status of agriculture in the national
economy has been further enhanced since the promulgation of the
Agriculture Law, while China has made increasing investment in
agriculture and intensified its invigoration through science and
education.
</P>
<P>
He requires that the inspectors increase their awareness of
this inspection and attach more importance to such issues as
prolonging the land contract period, easing the burdens on
farmers, agricultural input, and the popularization of
agricultural technology and circulation of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors should go deep into the grass-root units and
solicit opinions of grass-root officials and farmers to discover
both their achievements and their problems, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
