<HEADLINE> Kohl Calls Western, Russian Leaders on Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl held
separate telephone conservations with U.S. President Bill Clinton,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin over the weekend to discuss the current situation in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's spokesman Otto Hauser said that the chancellor expressed
in the telephone talks his "great concern" about the recent
development in Russia.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the stability of Russia and the continuation
of the political and economic reforms are of fundamental
importance for Europe and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also expressed the hope that the nomination of Russian
Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin would be approved by the
Russian State Duma (the lower house of parliament) and that
President Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin could win broadest possible
support in Russia for their reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
Kohl reiterated that under current circumstances, it was up to
Russia itself to push ahead with necessary reforms in order to
take the country out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of a leadership meeting of his Christian Democratic Union
(CDU) party on Monday, Kohl told reporters that the development
in Russia has immediate consequences for its neighboring countries
including Ukraine and the eastern European countries which are
applying for European Union membership.
</P>
<P>
"We must now make all efforts to support the reform forces in
Russia," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
According to Hauser, Kohl is also due to hold telephone talks
with Chernomyrdin, French President Jacques Chirac and other
leaders of the EU members and the G-7 group of Western
industrialized countries in the coming days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
