<HEADLINE> Cambodian Constitutional Council Rejects Poll Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Constitutional
Council rejected opposition parties' poll complaints Monday,
saying the complaints were "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The rejection by the nation's highest legislative body paved
the way for the National Election Committee (NEC) to announce the
official election results.
</P>
<P>
The two main opposition parties -- the royalist FUNCINPEC party
led by Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) of former
finance minister Sam Rainsy -- lodged 110 complaints to the
Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
Among the 17 complaints accepted by the council, two were put
to hearing Monday while the 15 others were ruled out.
</P>
<P>
Bin Chhin, spokesman of the Constitutional Council said that
all the complaints were considered "baseless."
</P>
<P>
He said the council was also looking into the opposition's
complaints that the NEC halted recounting for disputed communes
after only eight were completed. None of the recounts turned out
to be any hard evidence of rigging.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have called on the council to consider
recounting in roughly 800 communes, or about half of all counting
centers, where provisional results are disputed.
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC and SRP have been boycotting the results of the
election since the announcement of preliminary results early in
the month.
</P>
<P>
Since August 24, the main opposition parties have organized
massive sit-in protests in front of the National Assembly,
demanding proper response to their complaints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
