<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Banks Tighten Foreign Exchange Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's central bank has imposed
a ban on forward transactions conducted at spot rates, a move
bankers said aimed at tightening rules governing foreign exchange
trading at banks, a newspaper report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks must quote foreign exchange rates within the
limit permitted by the governor of the State Bank of Vietnam, the
Saigon Times quoted the bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
Banking institutions must not take advantage of the difference
between forward and spot rates to make profits under any form,
including non-deliverable forward contracts, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Banks are now banned from selling foreign currency at spot
rates to customers who have no immediate need.
</P>
<P>
Banks are only allowed to sell foreign currency to cover
customers' payments which have become due, such as for imports and
services provided by foreign companies, and for local and foreign
debts.
</P>
<P>
If banks sell foreign currency to corporate clients to pay
foreign debts, they must check documents and ensure the money
matches the tempo and schedule of payments, which have already
been registered at the state bank.
</P>
<P>
The ban is considered by bankers as a positive measure to stem
speculative deals.
</P>
<P>
The central bank made on Thursday a decision reducing forward
transactions with periods ranging from one to two weeks, and
setting fresh margin rates for such deals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0114 </DOCNO>
