<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Australian Stocks End 1.44 Percent Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Continued uncertainty in global
markets and heavy falls in several blue-chip stocks sent the
Australian share market tumbling 1.44 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index was down 36.2 points to
close at 2480.7, off an intra-day low of 2467.5.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of uncertainty in world markets and that is
putting pressure on our market," said Dicksons client adviser
Robert Holle.
</P>
<P>
The local bourse traded in negative territory from the start,
with the tone set by a 114.31-point drop on the Dow Jones
Industrial Average in New York which closed at 8051.68 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ord Minnett dealer Chris Shaw said sharp falls by News Corp,
diversified miner BHP and National Australia Bank stock were
together responsible for a large slice of the Australian market's
fall.
</P>
<P>
News Corp plunged 78.1 Australian cents, or 6.81 percent, to
10.69 Australian dollars while its preferred scrip dived 52.3
cents, or 5.20 percent, to close at 9.53 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the resources board, BHP shares tumbled 34 cents to the
five-year-low level of 12.06 Australian dollars, with resources
stocks generally succumbing to global market concerns and low
commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished the day 14.7 points lower at
916.1, while the all industrials index were down 62.8 points to
4409.0.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank ditched 32.7 cents to 21.62 Australian
dollars, contributing to a 99.4 point slide on the bank index to
5485.2.
</P>
<P>
Shaw said bank stocks were generally weaker on speculation of a
possible interest rate rise to prop up the weak Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank of Australia shed 24.8 cents to 18.66
Australian dollars, ANZ bank slid 21.8 cents to 8.83 Australian
dollars and Westpac bank dropped 20 cents to 9.30 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Diversified miner Rio Tinto fell 20 to 16.96 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 28.3 points to 843.6, and the spot
price of gold bullion in Sydney was 275.00 U.S. dollars an ounce
on Monday afternoon, up from Friday's close of 271.65 U.S. dollars
an ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 318.44 million shares traded for 789.53
million U.S. dollars, with falling stocks outnumbering rising
stocks 655 to 416. 
</P>
</TEXT>
