<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Likely to Lose in Duma Voting: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Russia's acting premier Viktor
Chernomyrdin will probably not survive the voting to be held
Monday in the State Duma (the lower house of parliament) for the
confirmation of his premiership, a senior Russian official said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The State Duma will most probably turn down Viktor
Chernomyrdin's candidacy today," Alexander Kotenkov, presidential
representative to the Duma, was quoted by the Itar-Tass news
agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Russia, which dominates the Duma, and
two other opposition parties expressed their determination to vote
against Chernomyrdin's candidacy during a parliamentary session
scheduled for 3:00 p.m. (1100 GMT) Monday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the report from the Interfax news
agency, Kotenkov also said that President Boris Yeltsin maintained
that Chernomyrdin was the candidate he proposed for the post of
prime minister ahead of the Duma's session.
</P>
<P>
Last week, opposition parties and the government drafted an
agreement that would give parliament more power over the make-up
of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin needs 226 votes to get the confirmation from the
450-member Duma, according to Russia's constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
