<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Revises Tariffs to Ward off Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Ports Authority (KPA)
is revising tariff rates and operational procedures to meet the
demands of a liberalized market and compete with the Tanzanian
Harbors Authority.
</P>
<P>
KPA Commercial Manager Francis Kinyeki was quoted by Monday's
East African newspaper as saying that the tariff schedules which
have been in effect since 1995 will terminate as soon as the
revision is complete.
</P>
<P>
Shipping sources said the changes are timely, in view of
rising competition from Tanzania's Dar es Salaam port, which has
been attracting more cargo from Uganda, Rwanda and the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
"The KPA should not be insensitive to change as it no longer
has a monopoly in the region," said an official of a leading
shipping line.
</P>
<P>
"The team charged with the revision of tariffs and operations
should make bold changes which will enable the port to compete
with others," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The KPA has in the past come in for criticism, particularly
from Uganda importers, over poor security at the port, vandalism
of goods and claims that the port had been taken over by
unscrupulous "briefcase" agents who charge exorbitant fees.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan importers have also complained that demurrage costs at
the Kenyan port are inflated, citing a case in which an importer
was asked to pay up to 22,000 U.S. Dollars when the actual cost
was 4,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan ministers in charge of transport, communications
and trade have discussed the complaints in a series of meetings
with their Kenyan counterparts and KPA bosses since last year.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan exporters and importers are the biggest users of
Mombasa port but have in recent years begun to explore the
northern route to the sea offered by Dar es Salaam, accessible
via the Inland Container Depot in western Kenya's Kisumu and Lake
Victoria ferry services.
</P>
<P>
Already, the KPA has liberalized some provisions in the tariff
structure to allow users to switch from road to rail at no cost,
also as an incentive to encourage use of rail transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
