<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Embankments To Be Fortified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- China plans to allocate 1.56
billion yuan (about 188 million U.S. dollars) over the next two
years to strengthen the embankments along the lower Yellow River
in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, designed to improve Shandong's flood control
ability, will focus on reinforcing and heightening the dikes,
dredging waterways, and enhancing the water-storage and
flood-diversion capacity of major lakes and reservoirs,
according to the Yellow River Water Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
As required by flood-control standards set for 2000, of the
629-kilometer Yellow River embankments in Shandong, 98.2
kilometers need to be raised, and 57 kilometers must be reinforced.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River is the second longest in China next to the
Yangtze, and because of serious silting the river bed continues to
rise, making it vulnerable to flooding.
</P>
<P>
This summer's devastating floods on the Yangtze has once again
put authorities related on the alert to fortify the Yellow
River embankments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
