<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Leaves to Attend Non-alignment Movement Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan left here for South Africa today to attend the 12th
Non-alignment Movement Summit to be held at Durban at the
invitation of Alfred Nzo, foreign minister of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Dlamini, South African ambassador to China, saw
Tang and the delegation off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
The convention, to be held at the turn of the century, is an
important meeting for the movement. More than 100 members and
observers of the movement will send delegations to attend it.
</P>
<P>
The Non-alignment Movement is an important political force in
the international arena. China has valued its constructive role in
the international affairs. China's relationship with the movement
has witnessed rapid progress since 1992, when the country obtained
the observer status of the movement.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have enhanced mutual trust in safeguarding world
peace and promoting human development and their cooperative ties
have shown promising prospects.  
