<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambians Urged to Cherish Cultural Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-president Christon
Tembo has urged his countrymen to cherish cultural values.
</P>
<P>
When officiating Sunday at the Kulamba ceremony of the Chewa
people in Katete, Eastern Province, Tembo told thousands of
people who attended the occasion that abandoning cultural values
would increase social problems.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the nation was headed for a serious social
catastrophe unless people take pride in their culture and its
values.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Monday quoted the vice-president as saying
that such ills as street kids and prostitution would escalate if
culture was under-played.
</P>
<P>
Tembo observed that due to the collapse of extended family
system in Zambia, orphans and deserted children were pouring the
streets without any hope of growing up into useful adults.
</P>
<P>
He said such children were exposed to dangers such as
prostitution and crimes.
</P>
<P>
"Traditionally, people with special needs were taken care of
through in-built safety net measures that were part of our
culture. Today the situation has changed, " said Tembo.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there was a serious need for the society to
re-discover its cultural roots to reduce such instances.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony also attracted some senior government officials
and several Chewa chiefs from Malawi and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Kulamba is an annual ceremony performed by subordinate chiefs
normally at the end of every August to show their thanks to the
tribe's Paramount Chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
