<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Village for One Million Resettlers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The five-member family tilled 1.6 hectares of low-yield, hilly
land which bore no crops during droughts.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement-oriented poverty-relief program was introduced
in 1995, with the central and autonomous regional government
pledging 3 billion yuan (about 361 million U.S. dollars) of
financial support. Building large power pumping stations to create
irrigated areas is considered a key to the program.
</P>
<P>
Ma Guangping, head of Baying Village, said each of his
villagers has received 0.133 hectare of irrigated land plus seeds,
fertilizer, technical assistance and 300 yuan of housing subsidy.
</P>
<P>
"We'll expect a good harvest in autumn," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xibao said he plans to buy tractors and grow fruit trees
next year, while neighbor Yang Shengcai wants to open a grain
processing mill.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou Shengxian, vice chairman of the regional
people's congress, the resettlement program also can help
alleviate soil erosion of the loess plateau, as the displacement
will enable tilled hilly land to be replanted with trees.
</P>
<P>
In the next two years, the autonomous region plans to build 16
more resettlers' townships designed for 478,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The program could be completed early next century, local
officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
