<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Develop Ginseng-based Drug for Curing Blood Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists claim they
have developed a ginseng-made pharmaceutical that proved to be
effective in the treatment of difficult blood diseases.
</P>
<P>
With more than 2 million yuan (about 240,000 U.S. dollars) in
funds from the Chinese and Australian governments, scientists from
Zhejiang Provincial Traditional Chinese Medicine Hospital have
successfully extracted and purified the necessary elements for the
medicine from ginseng, a traditional herbal tonic in China.
</P>
<P>
Ma Fengshun, a professor at the blood disease research center
at the hospital, said the clinic's use of the new pharmaceutical
in 23 cases of aplastic anemia and 33 cases of idiopathic
thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) demonstrated an effective rate of
82.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the pharmaceutical, after seven years of development,
has passed the appraisal of experts and won provincial awards for
scientific and technological advancement.
</P>
<P>
Gao Ruilan, another scientist at the center, said the natural
drug proved to be effective in helping generate white and red
blood cells and blood platelets.
</P>
<P>
It also helps curb leukemia cells when the patients are taking
anti-cancer drugs and reduce white blood cells caused by the
radiotherapy and chemical therapy, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the ginseng-made pharmaceutical is safe and
patients did not have any toxic reactions after taking the
pharmaceutical for two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Delhi Petrol Pumps to Market Unleaded Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- With an unenviable distinction
of being the fourth most polluted city in the world, New Delhi is
set to make a transition to unleaded petrol from Tuesday as part
of measures to contain air pollution.
</P>
<P>
All petrol pumps have been ordered by the Supreme Court to
market only unleaded petrol from September 1 and most of the
petrol stations have reportedly been phased out the leaded fuel.
</P>
<P>
Though unleaded petrol was introduced in the India's capital in
April 1995, the total phasing out of leaded petrol would be a
milestone in efforts to reduce air pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
Dilip Biswas, Chairman of the Central Pollution Control Board,
told reporters on Sunday that the environment friendly petrol
would have a maximum lead content of only 0.013 grams per liter.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that more than 85 percent of air-borne lead is
attributed to emissions from petrol-driven vehicles, Biswas said
pollution could not be immediately banished but one major lethal
substance would be out of air with a ban on leaded fuel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
