<HEADLINE> Leading African Ship Repair Firm Changes Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The African Marine and General
Engineering Company, sub-Saharan Africa's second largest ship
repair yard based in Kenya's port of Mombasa, has been sold to
Alba Petroleum Company.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old firm owns the only conventional dry docks on
the east African seaboard and is awarded the ISO quality system
certification in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
The sale was concluded by Claremont Holding Ltd, a subsidiary
of Alba Petroleum, and First Chartered Securities Group, the East
African newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alba Petroleum Ltd, a bunkering firm with substantial
interests in the shipping industry, will provide managerial
services.
</P>
<P>
"African Marine will benefit from Alba Petroleum's reputation
and wide knowledge of international shipping," said Andrew
Sinclair, the managing director of African Marine.
</P>
<P>
"It is anticipated that, as part of the Alba Group, African
Marine will expand not only in the shipping and marine
engineering field, but also in general engineering and steel
construction," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to reveal the sums involved in the sale
of the company, which also builds small vessels such as passenger
ferries, coasters, tugs, trawlers, launches and barges. 
</P>
