<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Village for One Million Resettlers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Xibao of the Hui ethnic
group was laying the last brick for his new three-room home. Not
far away, a primary school will be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
On the cobble road leading to Daying Resettlers Village, donkey
carts are shuttling back and forth, bringing villagers and old
furniture to their new homes.
</P>
<P>
The village is the first one specially built for resettlers
benefiting from a government poverty-relief program.
</P>
<P>
Designed to help one million mountain villagers of southern
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, the program is believed to be the
largest resettlement-oriented poverty-relief program now underway
in China.
</P>
<P>
With a population of five million, Ningxia in northwest China
is a region of Hui ethnic group, or Chinese muslims.
</P>
<P>
Daying Village in Guyuan County accommodates 156 families, all
of whom once lived in cave dwellings dozens of kilometers
away. Brick houses, electricity and a Yellow River water diversion
project are enabling them to begin a new and different life.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xibao, 47, told reporters that for three generations his
family had lived in two cave dwellings without electricity and
furnished only with a heated clay bed, a wooden suitcase and two
water vats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
