<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fear Rises After Bombing in E. Africa: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Personal security emerges as
the biggest single issue to worry people in Kenya and Tanzania in
the wake of the August 7 bombings at the two U.S. embassies, a
new opinion poll reveals.
</P>
<P>
The blasts killed 253 people including 12 Americans in Nairobi
and another 11 in Dar es Salaam, leaving more than 5,000 others
injured. The costs run into billions of Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the two east African states believe that the
targeting of their nations by anti-American extremists -- and the
U.S. reprisal missile attacks on Sudan and Afghanistan -- make
further attacks more, rather than less likely, showed the poll by
the Nation Media Group Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, 73 percent of those interviewed said they feel less
safe than before, compared with 16 percent who believed the
bombings have not changed their security.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the difference was slightly less marked, with 69
percent feeling less safe and 21 percent saying they felt
security was unchanged.
</P>
<P>
They want to see security increased particularly at the ports,
airports and border crossings in the two countries, the poll
showed.
</P>
<P>
The retaliatory U.S. raids will lead to even more terrorism in
the world, according to 48 percent of Kenyans interviewed and 34
percent of Tanzanians, while 11 percent of Kenyans and 24 percent
of Tanzanians felt the raids would lead to more terrorism in
their own countries.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen percent of Kenyans but a tiny four percent of
Tanzanians believed the raids would result in less terrorism.
</P>
<P>
People in both countries believe they were targeted because of
lax security. Forty-five percent of Kenyans blamed lax security,
while 26 percent said it was because of the U.S. presence.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-three percent of Kenyans and 97 percent of Tanzanians
thought the United States should compensate them for the August
blasts, saying the money should be paid by the U.S. as assistance
to the victims, as aid for reconstruction, economic rebuilding
and military support.
</P>
<P>
Two thousand people in Kenya and 1,000 in Tanzania have been
polled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0160 </DOCNO>
