<HEADLINE> 5 Israeli Soldiers Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Five Israeli soldiers were
wounded early Monday in an attack by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in south Lebanon, Lebanon's Voice of
the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The five were wounded in the explosion of a remote-controlled
bomb planted at the Dabshi village in the central sector of the
Israeli occupied zone in south Lebanon when an Israeli patrol was
passing by.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli radio said four Israeli soldiers were wounded by a
helicopter accident.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an Israeli army spokesman as saying that the
U.S.-made Bell 206 overturned on landing near the Dabshi village.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the People radio said following the blast,
Israeli helicopters landed at the site and evacuated the victims,
some of whom were reported to be seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah has claimed responsibility in a statement for the
attack, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The fresh casualties came a week after two Israelis were
killed by a Hezbollah roadside bomb in south Lebanon and followed
a Hezbollah Katyusha attack on Israel's north which wounded at
least 14 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Heavy losses the Israeli forces suffered in south Lebanon have
sparked heated debate in Israel on the wisdom of maintaining
troops in the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer self-styled security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from
cross-border attack by Lebanese guerrillas, while Lebanon's
resistance led by Hezbollah started to surge.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the Israeli cabinet endorsed the
20-year-old United Nations Resolution 425 but conditioned the
implementation on Beirut's guarantees for its northern security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected the offer and asked Israel to leave the
country without any preconditions as stipulated in the
resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
