<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Support for Bosnian Serb Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, August 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States supports the
incumbent Bosnian Serb leaders in Bosnia's September general
election and will approve 100 million U.S. dollars in assistance
to the Serb entity by the end of the year, according to reports
reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. commitment is based on condition that Bosnian Serbs
should implement the U.S.-brokered Dayton Accord that halted the
1992-95 Bosnian war, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
after talks with President of the Republika Srpska Bilijana
Plavsic and Prime Minister Milorad Dodik in Bijeljina.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she reminded the Bosnian Serb leaders that the
Dayton agreement could bring jobs and income to the Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
What's more, she added, if Bosnian Serbs implemented the
accord, especially the parts stipulating the return of refugees
and arrest of war criminals, they would get as much as one third
of the U.S. aid package for the entire Republic of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Bosnia consists of the Republika Srpska and the
Muslim-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
Albright told reporters that the Bosnian Serb leaders promised
they would implement all the clauses in the Dayton accord, as they
had done before.
</P>
<P>
On the Kosovo crisis, Albright said that the violence must stop
and the issue could only be resolved through diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the United States nor the European Allies can tolerate
much longer" what is going on in Kosovo, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concerns over the refugee exodus from Kosovo,
Albright announced that the U.S. would add 20 million dollars to
its assistance to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state traveled to Sarajevo on Sunday
evening for talks with Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and
Croat member of the Bosnian presidency Kresimir Zubak on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
