<HEADLINE> Sampras, Hingis Headline First Day at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Top seeds Pete Sampras of
the United States and defending champion Martina Hingis of
Switzerland highlight Monday's opening-round competition at the
$14 million U.S. Open Tennis Championships in New York.
</P>
<P>
Sampras will begin his quest for a record-tying 12th Grand
Slam title when he faces Germany's Marc-Kevin Goellner. Hingis,
in danger of losing her No. 1 ranking, will take on Polish
qualifier Aleksandra Olsza.
</P>
<P>
Four other men's seeded players are playing their first round
matches. Eighth seed Americna Andre Agassi, the 1994 champion,
will battle 20-year-old Frenchman Sebastian Grosjean tonight,
ninth seed Karol Kucera of Slovakia will face American Steve
Campbell. No.14 Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, a first-round loser
in 1994-95 and 1997 but a semi-finalist in 1996, will meet
Australia's Mark Woodforde; and No. 15 Alberto Berasategui of
Spain has a tough first round opponent in Austria's Thomas Muster.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, two-time champion Monica Seles of the Uni
ted States, the sixth seed, will meet Argentina's Florencia Labat
in a night match.
</P>
<P>
Also, ninth seed Irian Spirlea of Romania, who lost to Venus
Williams in a memorable semi-final match last year, will take on
Elena Likhovtsev of Russia; No. 11 Patty Schnyder of
Switzerland,who leads the women's tour with five titles this
year, will battle Japan's Yuka Yoshida; No. 14 Dominique van
Roost of Belgium will meet Frenchwoman Julie Halad-Decugis. No.
16 Ai Sugiyama of Japan will face Ruxandra Dragomir of Romania.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, a four-time champion, claimed his only Grand Slam
title of the year at Wimbledon and has won only three events this
year after going unbeaten in eight finals in 1997. He lost to
Petr Korda in the fourth round at last year's Open.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Sampras is tied with Bjorn Borg and idol Rod
Laver with 11 Grand Slam titles, one behind all-time leader Roy
Emerson. He is trying to finish the year at No. 1 a record sixth
straight year, but already has lost his top ranking twice to
Marcelo Rios of Chile.
</P>
<P>
Hingis became the second-youngest U.S. Open women's champion
last year with her victory over Venus Williams in the youngest
Grand Slam women's final in the Open Era.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Hingis has been stuck on four titles since the
Italian Open in early May. She has suffered nine losses this year
after dominating the women's tour with 12 titles and only five
match defeats in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hingis has held onto the top spot since March 31, 1997, but
could lose the No. 1 ranking to either Americna Lindsay Davenport
or Wimbledon champion Jana Novotna following this event.
</P>
<P>
Agassi has resurrected his career this year after a miserable
1997 which saw him fail to win a title and finish the year ranked
122nd. He has vaulted to the top 10 in the ATP rankings with four
titles and his 50 match wins -- including 44 on hardcourts --
lead the ATP Tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
