<HEADLINE> Croatia Stresses Strict Implementation of Dayton Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, August 30 (Xinhua) --Croatian President Franjo Tudjman
Sunday reiterated the strict implementation of the Dayton Accord
to resolve the Bosnian crisis, which he warned is not yet
completely over.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference here with visiting U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright after their hour-long meeting, Tudjman
described as "unacceptable" any attempt to revise the Dayton
agreement that ended the 1992-95 Bosnia war.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his country had vital interests in a peaceful
resolution to the Bosnian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Croatia "is obliged by its constitution to take care of Croats
outside the Republic of Croatia," Tudjman noted.
</P>
<P>
Croats now account for 12 percent of Bosnia's population.
</P>
<P>
He urged the United States to help establish a special
relationship between Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman said Croatia would continue all-round cooperation with
the United States and expressed the hope that Albright's visit
would help further improve Croatia's relations with the United
States, Europe and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her part, said the United States would continue to
support Zagreb's efforts to build democracy and develop economy.
</P>
<P>
She praised Croatia for making "some good progress" in letting
Croatian Serb refugees return to their homes as well as in
cooperating with the international tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
"Modern Croatia should welcome home all people that lived here
before the war," said Albright.
</P>
<P>
She also urged Croatia to do more in its political reforms and
respect for a free media.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Albright met with Croatia's opposition
leaders, Archbishop Josip Bozanic and independent journalists
before going to Bosnia to give support for September's general
election there. 
</P>
