<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA -- Following some easing of market tensions in Asia in
the earlier part fo the year, a new round of turbulence erupted in
Asia in the second quarter of 1998, said the Basle-based Bank for
International Settlements (BIS) in a report to be published Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Nervousness about economic and financial conditions in Japan
accentuated the coolness towards yen-denominated assets," said the
BIS in its report of International Banking and Financial Market
Development.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, problems of policy credibility in several
Asian countries put downward pressures on currencies in the
region, with markets paying increasing attention to the risk of a
devaluation of the Chinese yuan," it said.
</P>
<P>
The BIS said that these events, together with the weakness of
commodity prices and, in some countries, political uncertainty,
initiated a new wave of contagion to other emerging market
economies, triggering a flight towards the perceived safe-haven
markets of the United States and Europe. (Asia Financial Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair and U.S. President
Bill Clinton Sunday discussed the Russian financial crisis by
telephone, urging Russia to carry on its reform program.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman was quoted by Reuters as saying
Sunday evening: "There was clear agreement (between Blair and
Clinton) that we're ready to help Russia, but only if Russia is
ready to pursue further economic reform."
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, Blair, whose country is the current
Group of Seven (G7) president, had a series of telephone
discussions with other G7 leaders. (US-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin is
confident in overcoming the current crisis in the country,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview Chernomyrdin said Sunday evening that
"We know what first steps to take to improve the situation." I am
sure it is possible to overcome the crisis in the country," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin stressed that "We cannot waste time. The country
cannot live without a government."
</P>
<P>
Talking about the political accord worked on by heads of the
presidential administration, government and parliament in the
morning, Chernomyrdin said that "I am very glad that this document
was prepared by us, not working groups, or assistants or
consultants. We coordinated it in advance." (Russia-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Oil production and export systems in Iraq are in
critical conditions due to the delayed arrival of spare parts and
production requirements for oil installations, said an Iraqi Oil
Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency on Sunday, the
unnamed source said without spare parts, it is hard for Iraq to
repair any accidental failure now.
</P>
<P>
So far Iraq has signed 111 contracts valued at 100 million
U.S. dollars to purchase oil spare parts, but the U.N. Sanctions
Committee has approved only seven and put on hold five others,
said the source. (Iraq-Oil-Spare Parts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Saturday it was encouraged
by acting Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's quick
reassurances about his country's crumbling economy.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, re-appointed by President Boris Yeltsin this
week, earlier Saturday ruled out any return to Russia's Soviet
past and also assembled a group of senior reformers to prepare
urgent measures to halt the country's financial
crisis. (US-Russia-Economy) 
