<HEADLINE> Communist Leader Opposes Chernomyrdin's Nomination as PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia's three major party
leaders expressed their opposition Sunday to the appointment of
Viktor Chernomyrdin as Russian prime minister, casting a shadow
again over the solution to the Russian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Zyuganov, chairman of the Russian Communist Party, said
Sunday at Russia's Independence TV program that he would persuade
all Communist parliamentary members to vote against Chernomyrdin's
nomination at the Duma (lower house) meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Communist parliamentary fraction will not sign the
political agreement drafted by Russia's interim government and
parliamentary leaders Saturday in a bid to end the country's
crisis, said Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would give legislators more powers over Cabinet
appointments and government policy in exchange for quick
confirmation of the nomination. But Zyuganov said the agreement
could not guarantee anything to anybody.
</P>
<P>
Grigory Yavlinsky and Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who respectively
lead the Yabloko bloc and the Liberal Democratic Party, also
voiced opposition to the nomination on the TV program.
</P>
<P>
On August 23, President Boris Yeltsin brought back Chernomyrdin
as prime minister to replace the young Sergei Kiriyenko, who
stayed in office for only two months, in the hope that the
familiar figure would help curb the worsening trend of the
country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
