<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Trade Deficit Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh had a trade deficit of
2,854 million U.S. dollars during the 1997-98 fiscal year, up 5.63
percent from the preceding 1996-97 fiscal, a press report here
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit, which accounted for 9 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP), was the result of trade
imbalance between the country's imports of 8,015 million dollars
and exports of 5,160.2 million dollars during the fiscal year
ending June 30, 1998, The New Nation daily quoted the central
bank, Bangladesh Bank, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The country's imports and exports in the past fiscal year
registered a growth of 8.60 percent and 16.82 percent respectively
over the previous fiscal.
</P>
<P>
Imports from India alone accounted for over 15 percent of the
country's total imports, while exports to India took up only
around 1.3 percent of its total exports.
</P>
<P>
In the total export earnings, the contribution of garment
sector was 55.1 percent, followed by hosiery and knitwear 18.2
percent, jute and jute goods 8.3 percent, and frozen food 5.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
Remittances of Bangladeshi nationals working abroad amounted to
1,433 million dollars in fiscal 1997-98, short of the
government-targeted 1,700 million dollars and a slight decrease
from 1,475 million dollars in the 1996-97 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
