<HEADLINE> Japan Aids Sri Lanka's Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
provided assistance of 189 million U.S. dollars to Sri Lanka for a
series of development projects in the fields of electricity,
telecommunications, environment and bridge construction, according
to official sources Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry sources said the assistance included an
outright grant of 3.3 million U.S. dollars and the remaining 185.7
million dollars is a concessionary loan at an interest rate of 1.8
percent repayable in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The grant loan will be used to rehabilitate five bridges
identified as the Master Plan Study on Bridge Development by the
Japan International Cooperation Agency.
</P>
<P>
The concessionary loan is to finance four major development
projects in the country. The first is to strengthen the capability
of The National Transmission Network, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The second project is the Electricity Board's Medium Voltage
Distribution Network Reinforcement Project. Another is a
Telecommunication Network Expansion Project in Metro area in
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that an Environmentally Friendly Solutions
Fund Program will be the fourth project to be benefited through
this loan scheme. 
</P>
