<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panamanians Reject Reelection of President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian voters, in a
national referendum Sunday, rejected a proposed constitutional
reform intended to allow the incumbent president to seek
reelection.
</P>
<P>
With 82.6 percent of ballots counted, the anti-reform side won
63.7 percent of the votes in the referendum against 34.5 percent
for reform supporters, or 595,960 votes to 322,935.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.7 million Panamanians were eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
The reform would eliminate the constitutional restriction that
does not allow President Ernesto Perez Balladares to be reelected
to another five-year term unless he sits out two terms.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of the reform said the permission of immediate
presidential reelection will assure smooth handover of the Panama
Canal and U.S. military land scheduled for December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, the critics against the reform hold that such reform
would bring back dictatorship to the country.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the initial results of the referendum were
announced, the president praised the referendum as proof of
Panama's growing strength as a democracy and said he would proudly
hand power to his successor next year.
</P>
<P>
Critics charged that Perez Balladares was trying to hold power
to put friends of his Democratic Revolutionary Party in the best
position to profit from the Dec. 31, 1999, handover of the Panama
Canal.
</P>
<P>
Panama's next president will be elected in May and take office
in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
