<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Eyes Europe, Japan for Global Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Ministry of Thailand
is eyeing Europe and Japan as possible alternatives for the
government's global bonds since market conditions in the United
States became unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. financial market is virtually closed to all Asian
countries and Thailand will have to look for new trading places to
sell the bonds, the Bangkok Post said Monday, quoting government
spokesman Akrapol Sorasuchart.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry plans to issue 200 billion baht (5 billion
U.S. dollar) worth of the bonds internationally to generate income
to restructure the debts of the Financial Institution Development
Fund.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Chatumongol Sonakul has said the
government would have to offer interest rates of up to five
percentage points above those paid on U.S. treasury bills, of
about 12 percent, if the bonds were issued in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Bonds carrying such high rates would become risky when they
were traded in the secondary market, and the initial subscribers
might face huge losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
