<HEADLINE> Steel Mill Privatized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 31 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has
privatized a state-owned steel mill here by leasing it to local
private entrepreneurs for continuous running at full capacity and
boosting production.
</P>
<P>
According to a lease contract signed on Sunday between the No.3
State Mining Enterprise and the National Industrial Holding Ltd.,
a local private enterprise, the latter is to invest in
manufacturing steel and other construction materials after taking
over the Ywama Steel Mill in Yangon, the New Light of Myanmar
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The steel mill is the first largest industry leased out since
Myanmar began its privatization plan in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase privatization plan of the country covers 51
state-owned economic enterprises including processing and
manufacturing factories, cinemas and livestock breeding farms.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process has been under way in various forms
including auctioning and leasing out the enterprises or
establishing joint ventures with local and foreign entrepreneurs
or operating either under buy-back or counter-trade system.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, about 140 state-run
cinemas, some 42 factories and two livestock breeding farms were
designated to be sold through competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than two dozen state-owned saw mills have been
reportedly privatized.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's gross domestic
product in the 1997-98 fiscal year, which ended in March, grew by
4.6 percent over the previous year, in which the private sector
contributed 75.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
