<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Discover New Ozone-destroying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 31 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists said
Monday they had discovered a new ozone-destroying chemical in the
atmosphere, as positive signs emerge that damage to the ozone
layer should decline in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Halon-1202, which has an ozone depletion potential
approximately half that of the common chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs),
has increased five-fold in the atmosphere since the late 1970s,
the Commonwealth Scientific, Industrial Research Organization
(CSIRO), the leading national research group in Australia, said in
a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
The figures were obtained by collecting the measurements of
pristine air at the Australian Bureau of Meteorology's Cape Grim
baseline air pollution station in northwestern Tasmanian state.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years the atmospheric concentration of
halon-1202 has been growing at 17 percent per year, the
organization said.
</P>
<P>
"The source of the new halon is a mystery, adding to
scientists' concern over its potential impact on the ozone layer,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
The ozone layer, located about 24 km above the earth, is a
shield against the sun's deadly ultraviolet radiation.
</P>
<P>
Paul Fraser, an expert from CSIRO Atmospheric Research, said,
"The rapid growth of halon-1202 comes as a surprise to us."
</P>
<P>
Fraser speculates that gas may be by-product of inefficient
production of other halons in developing countries, and some
countries might be manufacturing halon-1202 for military
applications.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to consider imposing a
ban on production of halon-1202 in order to protect the ozone
layer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980831.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
