<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair and U.S. President
Bill Clinton Sunday discussed the Russian financial crisis by
telephone, urging Russia to carry on its reform program.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman was quoted by Reuters as saying
Sunday evening: "There was clear agreement (between Blair and
Clinton) that we're ready to help Russia, but only if Russia is
ready to pursue further economic reform."
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, Blair, whose country is the current
Group of Seven (G7) president, had a series of telephone
discussions with other G7 leaders.
</P>
<P>
"There is a clear agreement among the G7 leaders that it is in
all our interests to make sure Russia gets through this crisis and
it is best do so by sticking to the reform path," another Downing
Street spokesman said early Sunday. (UK-US-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Leaders of the Group of Seven (G7)leading
industrial nations have pledged to encourage Russia to press ahead
with its economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman told reporters Sunday that British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who discussed the Russian financial
situation by telephone with other G7 leaders over the weekend,
said the G7 countries felt it was in all their interests to ensure
Russia sticks to its reform path.
</P>
<P>
"There is a clear feeling among the G7 leaders that it is in
all our interests to make sure Russia gets through this crisis and
it will best do so by sticking to the reform path," the spokesman
quoted Blair as saying. (UK-G7-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian Communist Party faction will not sign the
draft political agreement and will vote against the candidature of
Viktor Chernomyrdin to the post of prime minister, leader of the
communist party Gennady Zyuganov stated on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov's remarks came Sunday evening after a conference of
the executive and legislative authorities at the State Duma and an
emergency meeting of the Communist Party Central Committee's
presidium in the NTV Itogy television program.
</P>
<P>
In the Itogy television program leader of the Liberal
Democratic faction Vladimir Zhirinovsky said his faction will not
give a single vote to Chernomyrdin as a candidate to the Russian
premier.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a group of governors will appeal to the
Russian president on Monday morning for submitting to the State
Duma a list of three candidates to the premier's post.
(Russia-Nomination)
</P>
<P>
