<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owen Detroy Newcastle's Dream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Liverpool's teenage star Michael
Owen destroyed Newcastle's dreams of a successful start under new
boss Ruud Gullit with a hat-trick in the first half at the
English Premier league on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Gullit had received the adulation of the St James' Park crowd
before the game but must have wished that he had Owen on his
roster as he watched from the stands.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool started the game with Steve McManaman in a roving
role, finding plenty of space and penetration.
</P>
<P>
After 17 minutes the Liverpool captain Paul Ince powered a
shot from 20 yards which Shay Given in the Newcastle goal could
only parry.
</P>
<P>
Owen nipped in from the right and finished on the near post as
Given struggled to get to his feet.
</P>
<P>
One minute later Owen was given a chance to run at the
Newcastle defence and he did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
The youngster's pace told as he left Phillip Albert for dead
and drilled his shot through Given's legs.
</P>
<P>
Ten minutes later Newcastle new-boy Stephane Guivarc'h sealed
his debut with a goal which was against the run of play.
</P>
<P>
But Owen completed his hat-trick on 32 minutes after running
past two Newcastle defenders and curling a shot with the outside
of his right foot past the despairing Given
</P>
<P>
Newcastle were looking for the half-time whistle to be blown
but a minute before the break Patrik Berger made a run down the
left before cutting inside and finishing clinically.
</P>
<P>
Half-time substitute Warren Barton, on for Serrant, allowed
the Magpies to play a more solid back four instead of three in
the middle.
</P>
<P>
Guivarc'h continued to win the odd ball in dangerous positions
but his partnership with Alan Shearer needs much more
understanding.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman's 62nd minute header looped over the bar as
Newcastle continued to have all the play.
</P>
<P>
Shearer then hit a powerful left foot effort but it struck
Babb as it headed for the bottom corner.
</P>
<P>
The game dribbled to its inevitable conclusion with Liverpool
having nothing more to prove and Newcastle struggling to find any
form.
</P>
<P>
Some of the usually ultra-loyal Newcastle fans left the ground
before the end of the game and Gullit will have to win the
confidence of the Magpies supporters after this crushing defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
