<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Suffers from Renewed Financial Turbulence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 30 (Xinhua) -- Following some easing of market
tensions in Asia in the earlier part fo the year, a new round of
turbulence erupted in Asia in the second quarter of 1998, said the
Basle-based Bank for International Settlements (BIS) in a report
to be published Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Nervousness about economic and financial conditions in Japan
accentuated the coolness towards yen-denominated assets," said the
BIS in its report of International Banking and Financial Market
Development.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, problems of policy credibility in several
Asian countries put downward pressures on currencies in the
region, with markets paying increasing attention to the risk of a
devaluation of the Chinese yuan," it said.
</P>
<P>
The BIS said that these events, together with the weakness of
commodity prices and, in some countries, political uncertainty,
initiated a new wave of contagion to other emerging market
economies, triggering a flight towards the perceived safe-haven
markets of the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the repercussions outside Asia were more profound
than in the first episode of contagion, amplified by concerns
about the situation in Russia and in other countries suffering
form macroeconomic imbalances and/or the weakness of commodity
prices, oil in particular, said the BIS.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, in May, a number of non-Asian emerging market economies
were forced to further tighten fiscal and monetary policies," the
BIS said.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a better differentiation of country risk by
international investors, the BIS said, Latin American debt was, at
the end of the quarter, still trading at a significant discount
compared with prices prevailing in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
"The resurgence of financial turbulence in the second quarter
of 1998 lent a new sense of urgency to addressing the issues of
crisis prevention and resolution," the BIS pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It said that national and international authorities should
continue to face difficult trade-offs, such as the need to
reconcile domestic and external constraints and to provide
liquidity while limiting the risk of moral hazard through an
appropriate sharing of the financial costs of crises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
