<HEADLINE> Romania: Budget Revision Triggers Powerful Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 28 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Government has
begun debates over the draft Ordinance on the 1998 state budget's
revision, by reducing sums allocated to ministries by 8,000
billion lei (about 900 million U.S. dollars), about 10 percent of
the current budget and 2 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product(GDP).
</P>
<P>
Since the spending cuts is the only way to cover a part of the
budgetary deficit, all the ministers have formally accepted it.
But the agreement of principle over this measure was not
automatically accepted by the Government members. It is known so
far that the National Education, Health, Culture and Transport
ministries are of the most hit, the reactions of the holders of
these portfolios are prompt.
</P>
<P>
The minister of the National Education Andrei Marga said that
his ministry's cuts by 1,000 billion lei (112 million U.S.
dollars) "are absolutely unacceptable and will have serious
consequences on education." He said that his ministry needs
another 800 billion lei (90 million dollars) this year and cannot
accept any reduction.
</P>
<P>
The Health Minister Hajdu Gabor in his turn says the
diminishing by circa 100 billion lei (11 million U.S. dollars)
will be extremely painful for his ministry, and specifies that
ways to face the situation would be giving up investments, cut
hospitals' spending and blocking vacancies in the field.
</P>
<P>
Culture Minister Ion Caramitru shows no enthusiasm face to his
ministry's budget revision. The spending will drop 74 billion lei
(8.3 million U.S. dollars), which will affect firstly the already
started investments works.
</P>
<P>
The National Defence Minister Victor Babiuc is another unhappy
one. The ministry he runs will lose at least 4 percent of the
given budget.
</P>
<P>
The Prime minister said he supported the budget revision
proposed by Minister of Finance Daniel Daianu since "there is no
other better solution and an increase in the budget deficit can
not be accepted."
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Finance saw the revision as justified since
otherwise there could be a risk for the budget deficit to jump to
over 5.5-6 percent, from the initial target of 3.6 percent GDP.
</P>
<P>
According to sources of the government, no decision was made
till now over the issue and the draft Ordinance will be discussed
during an extraordinary government session on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
